## Associations among Variables



<div class='question-begin'>Question 2</div><div class='question-body'>


Create a scatterplot of wellbeing score and social interactions *before* calculating the correlation between them.  

Making reference to both the plot and correlation coefficient, describe the association between wellbeing and social interactions among participants in the Edinburgh & Lothians sample. 

:::{.callout-tip appearance="simple" collapse="true"}

### Hint

*Plot*  
We are trying to investigate how wellbeing varies by varying numbers of weekly social interactions. Hence, wellbeing is the dependent variable (on the y-axis), and social interactions is the independent variable (on the x-axis). Checking the [bivariate examples flashcard](https://uoepsy.github.io/dapr2/2425/labs/1_b1_reading.html#visual-exploration) might help. 

*Correlation*  
Have a look at [this set of flashcards](https://uoepsy.github.io/dapr2/2425/labs/1_b1_reading.html#correlation) for all things correlation. Remember to round your numbers in-line with [APA 7th edition guidelines](https://uoepsy.github.io/dapr2/2425/labs/1_b1_reading.html#apa-formatting). The `round()` function will come in handy here.

:::



</div><p class="question-end"></p>





<div style="display:none;">



Let's produce a scatterplot:


::: {.cell layout-align="center"}

```{.r .cell-code}
ggplot(data = mwdata, aes(x = social_int, y = wellbeing)) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(x = "Social Interactions (Number per Week)", 
       y = "Wellbeing (WEMWBS) Scores")
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![Association between Wellbeing and Social Interactions](1_01_slr_files/figure-html/fig-mwdata-scatterplot-1.png){#fig-mwdata-scatterplot fig-align='center' width=80%}
:::
:::


To comment on the strength of the linear association we compute the correlation coefficient in either of the following ways:

::: {.panel-tabset}

## Index dataframe (`[]`)


::: {.cell layout-align="center"}

```{.r .cell-code}
# correlation matrix of the two columns of interest - (check with columns we need, in this case 3 & 5)
round(cor(mwdata[,c(3,5)]), digits = 2)
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}
```
           social_int wellbeing
social_int       1.00      0.24
wellbeing        0.24      1.00
```
:::
:::


## Variable selection (`select()`)


::: {.cell layout-align="center"}

```{.r .cell-code}
# select only the columns we want by name, and pass this to cor()
mwdata %>% 
  select(social_int, wellbeing) %>%
  cor() %>%
    round(digits = 2)
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}
```
           social_int wellbeing
social_int       1.00      0.24
wellbeing        0.24      1.00
```
:::
:::


:::

And we can see that via either method, the correlation is 
$$
r_{\text({Social~Interactions,~~ Wellbeing})} = .24
$$
<br>

::: {.callout-important icon=false appearance="minimal"}

There was a weak, positive, linear association between the weekly number of social interactions and WEMWBS scores for the participants in the sample ($r$ = .24). More social interactions were associated, on average, with higher wellbeing scores.

:::

<br>



</div><p class="solution-end"></p>



